spanGrp.span: transcribed by ER in August 2008; seems to be OK
no, you can also start in the Nǀuu language
nee, jy kan ook op die Nǀuu taal begin,
nee, jou kan ook op die Nǀuu taal begin
it sounds like /si xa/, but E corrects herself to /sa xa/; check why! because of PST?
we go so that the children go and dance
si ǁʼaa sii, nǀa ǀoeke ǁʼng ǀqoqon,
gaan ons lat die kinders loop dans
what is the second /si(i)/? first repeated by E as /si ǁʼae si nǀa .../, later left out; check, it is there on the recording! later E repeats /si ǁʼae nǀa/
then we go, and we go to sleep(?)
a si ǁʼae, si ǁʼaa, si ʘunn,
toe loop ons, toe loop slaap ons
strange structure and translation; I don't hear the second /si/; I hear a /ng/ instead, but E rejects it (might be phonetical); she insists on /si/
first /ǁʼae/ is [ǁʼae], second is /ǁʼaa/; check why! E repeats /si ǁʼaa si ... ʘunn/ at least five times!!!; is it a postverbal pronoun again; cf. preceding record!!!
(we) walk around, walk around, walk around
dyaqnn tyiin, dyaqnn tyiin, dyaqnn tyiin,
loop rond, loop rond, loop rond
E says /kiin/ ('around') here is not the same as /kinn/ 'lê', but she says they sound similar
the "Schmidtsdrift" people live at Platfontein today
they dance, they dance, (then) three persons go out
kinn ǀqoqon, kinn ǀqoqon, nǁngǂee ni nǃona ǁʼng,
hulle dans, hulle dans, daar gaan drie mense uit
three persons step out of the circle of the other dancers

E always mixes up the eland and the kudu in this story; every time when she says 'eland' here, she actually means 'kudu'; in the kudu dance, one of the dancer plays the kudu; another one or two act as dog, and other people play hunters
probably not /ǁʼae/ but /nǁae/; is this the same?? it sounds more like [nǁae] here, but E repeats it first as [nǁae], later as [ǁʼae]
it eats, it eats, it eats
ha aan, ha aan, ha aan,
hy wei, hy wei, hy wei

check the word for 'other'; is this a noun? E says it means 'die anders'; it is in the dic, but Sven thinks it might just be /ǂee ng koke/; I don't think so, but check; E says /ǂann/ alone is not OK; it must be /ǂann ng koke/
(they) hunt, hunt, hunt hunt together with the dog
ǀkxʼoan, ǀkxʼoan, ǀkxʼoan, ǀkxʼoan nǀa ǂhunn,
(hulle) jag, jag, jag, jag saam met die hond
die hond kry die ding (die eland) ...
according to E: /ǁʼann/ = 'it smells (e.g. good, bad)', or 'it smells like X'; 'to smell something (vtr)' is /ǃkhao/
the verb is German 'traben'; check transcription (080825E-00, elic. with C and F)
he catches it (the kudu), he barks, he barks
ha hoo ki, ha baqoke, ha baqoke,
hy kry hom, hy blaf, hy blaf
check recording! the first verbs sounds like [ǃai], but I don't know what it is; E gave two different versions of that
it (the kudu) wants to ?bump (here: with the head) ...
hy (die koedoe) wil stoot (met die kop, horing) ...
the dog, ?bump?the dog, the people come, come, come, come
ǂhunn, ǃʼhuun ǂhunn, nǁngǂee saa, saa, saa, saa,
die hond, stoot die hond, die mense kom, kom, kom, kom
die ander man steek hom (die koedoe)
not repeated as [ǁʼae], but as [nǁae] and translated as 'toe'; maybe the two are not the same
another man slaps the dog (to make him go away from the kudu)
die ander man slaat die hond
acc. to E: /ǂauke/ is 'hit one time, slap, smack', ǂamʼa/ is 'beat, trash' ('richtig verprügeln, mehrmals schlagen'); check
/ǂoo ko/ vs. /ǂoo a ko/: E says the /a/ is not there and is not obligatory, but it would be better with /a/; check!
the other man stabs it (the kudu), it lies down
ǂoo ko ǁqann ki, ki kiin,
die ander man steek hom (die koedoe), hy lê
E first translated /kiin/ as 'val', then she corrects herself to 'lê'
(then) they (the three "actors") come back again dancing, (they) come dancing, come dancing, then all the people ...
kinn gǀoe ǀqoqon saa, ǀqoqon saa, ǀqoqon saa, nǁngǂee huniki
toe kom hulle dans weer terug, kom dans, kom dans, nou alle mense ...
nice SVC with /saa/ as V2; seems to be different from /sii/ or /saa/ as V1
when E repeats slowly, it is [ǃʼoakekerake]; when speaking fast, it is sometimes [ǃʼoatyakerake]
clap hands, clap hands, they dance, dance, dance
ǃqoeke, ǃqoeke, kinn ǀqoqon, ǀqoqon, ǀqoqon,
klap hande, klap hande, hulle dans, dans, dans
a ng ǀoeke xa gǀoe ǀqoqonwa,
en my het kinders ook gedans
/ǀoeke/ is [ǀoetye] from E in fast speech
PL: /ǀkhuike/; generic term for 'bird'; /ǀkhuisi nǃain/ 'big bird' (acc. to E)
I take a young girl, I put her into the "hok"
ng ǀai ǁhaiǀaa, ng ǀʼee ng nǁng ǁaʼen,
toe vat ek 'n jong meisie en sit haar in die hok
young girls are put into the "hok", a small hut or chamber, when they start to menstruate; here, E and here children put a girl into the "hok" symbolically in their dance
they dance until the young girl can come out of her "hok"
we dance, we dance, the children dance, the children dance
si ǀqoqon, si ǀqoqon, ǀoeke ǀqoqon, ǀoeke ǀqoqon,
ons dans, ons dans, die kinders dans, die kinders dans
the piece of cloth from the girl's head
die doek van die meisie haar kop
E repeats with and without the /se/ 'GEN' marker; E says /au ǁquu/ and /ǀai ǁquu/ have the same meaning
the girl's head or face was covered with a piece of cloth so that other people can't look at her
the young girl dances, dances, dances
die jong miesie dans, dans, dans

E says /ǁhaiǀaa/ is 'die hokmeisie', or a girl at this age; later, when she gets older, she becomes a /ǃʼoakerasi/; E is not really sure about it; she thinks after the hok you could maybe be a /ǃʼoakerasi/; the age for becoming a ǃʼoakerasi might be around 12 or 13 years; later you are a /ǃʼoakerasi/ until you get married; then you become a /ǀaeki/; a small child is a /ǀoba ʘuun/ or a /ǀaeki ʘuun/; if you have children, can be either be called just /ǀaeki/, or /ǀaeki ǁʼorake/; but everything is very unsure
we dance, dance with the young girl
ons dans, dans met die jong meisie
alternative translation: 'nou is ons klaar met die dans'; /si nou tyoa/
now all (= all kinds of) dances ...
kann sein, dass ich E das /-ke/ 'PL' suffix an /ǀqoqon/ eingeredet habe; es könnte auch einfach /-ki/ 'NOM' sein
translation given by E 'daar was nog verskillene (lit.: alle) danse'
E says the /nǁaa/ is the same word as 'stay' here; check
what is the wrong word here? /nǁng/ '3PL'?
what the other dances' names are
[ǀqoqon] ǀqoqonke ng koke se ǀeen dyee ka,
wat is die ander danse se naam nie

check structure: 1. What is the question's structure? 2. Is the last word /ka/ 'say' (E says maybe) and is "dyee" really /dyee/? AND 3.: Is the /-ke/ really 'PL', or was it again forced by me, and it is just /-k/ 'NOM'i? cf. also rec. 071 etc.
E repeats /... se ka ǀeen .../, but there is no /ka/ on the recording
E translates: 'die dans was mooi'; check again
